nodes.label: Parallel and distributed system introduction
nodes.title: Parallel and distributed system introduction
nodes.description: Parallel and distributed system introduction: An overview of computing systems that involve multiple processors or computers working together to solve a problem.

nodes.label: Computing_system_terminology
nodes.title: Computing_system_terminology
nodes.description: Computing_system_terminology: Key terms and concepts related to computing systems, such as processors, memory, storage, and networking.

nodes.label: Why_parallel_computing?
nodes.title: Why_parallel_computing?
nodes.description: Why_parallel_computing?: Exploring the motivations behind parallel computing, including the need for increased computational power and efficiency.

nodes.label: Moore's_law
nodes.title: Moore's_law
nodes.description: Moore's_law: The observation that the number of transistors on a microchip doubles approximately every two years, leading to exponential growth in computing power.

nodes.label: Power_wall
nodes.title: Power_wall
nodes.description: Power_wall: The limit on the amount of power that can be dissipated by a microprocessor, which poses a challenge to further increasing clock speeds and performance.

nodes.label: Dennard_Scaling
nodes.title: Dennard_Scaling
nodes.description: Dennard_Scaling: The principle that as transistors shrink in size, their power density remains constant, allowing for increased performance without a significant increase in power

nodes.label: Performance_and_speedup
nodes.title: Performance_and_speedup
nodes.description: Performance_and_speedup: Measurement of how well a system performs a task, often quantified by the speedup achieved compared to a reference system or baseline.

nodes.label: Hardware_metrics
nodes.title: Hardware_metrics
nodes.description: Hardware_metrics: Metrics, e.g., latency, throughput, speed up, scaling

nodes.label: Scaling_and_scaling_law
nodes.title: Scaling_and_scaling_law
nodes.description: Scaling_and_scaling_law: The study of how system performance changes as the size of the system (such as the number of processors) increases

nodes.label: Amdahl's_law
nodes.title: Amdahl's_law
nodes.description: Amdahl's_law: A formula that predicts the maximum speedup that can be achieved by parallelizing a computation

nodes.label: Gustafson’s_law
nodes.title: Gustafson’s_law
nodes.description: Gustafson’s_law: A complementary principle to Amdahl's Law, which argues that larger problems can often be parallelized more effectively

nodes.label: Efficiency
nodes.title: Efficiency
nodes.description: Efficiency: The ratio of useful work performed by a system to the total energy expended or resources consumed

nodes.label: Parallel_Architecture
nodes.title: Parallel_Architecture
nodes.description: Parallel_Architecture: The design and organization of hardware systems that support parallel processing, involving multiple processors or processing units.

nodes.label: Michael_Flynn_Texonomy
nodes.title: Michael_Flynn_Texonomy
nodes.description: Michael_Flynn_Texonomy: A classification system proposed by Michael Flynn that categorizes parallel computer architectures based on the number of instruction streams and data streams,resulting in four categories: SISD, SIMD, MISD, and MIMD.

nodes.label: Parallelism options
nodes.title: Parallelism options
nodes.description: Parallelism options: options include CPU level, e.g., multi core, many core, machine level, e.g., shared memory, distributed memory.

nodes.label: Parallel_Application
nodes.title: Parallel_Application
nodes.description: Parallel_Application: Software or programs designed to execute tasks concurrently on multiple processors or cores

nodes.label: Terminology
nodes.title: Terminology
nodes.description: Terminology: e.g., amount of work, span, speed of concurrency, average degree of concurrency, computational, communication, synchronization, granularity, locality.

nodes.label: Design_method
nodes.title: Design_method
nodes.description: Design_method: Methodologies and approaches used in the design of parallel systems

nodes.label: Multi_threading
nodes.title: Multi_threading
nodes.description: Multi_threading: A programming model that allows multiple threads of execution to run concurrently within the same process, enabling parallelism and efficient resource utilization.

nodes.label: Programming model
nodes.title: Programming model
nodes.description: Programming model: An abstraction that defines the methods and constructs used by developers to create parallel programs, including APIs, libraries, and language features.

nodes.label: POSIX_threads
nodes.title: POSIX_threads
nodes.description: POSIX_threads : A standardized threading API for Unix-like operating systems, providing a set of functions and data types for creating and managing threads.

nodes.label: OpenMP
nodes.title: OpenMP
nodes.description: OpenMP: An API that supports multi-platform shared-memory multiprocessing programming in C, C++, and Fortran, providing compiler directives, runtime library routines, and environment variables for parallel programming.

nodes.label: Race condition
nodes.title: Race condition
nodes.description: Race condition: A situation that occurs in concurrent programming when the outcome of the execution depends on the relative timing or interleaving of operations performed by multiple threads

nodes.label: Parallelism options
nodes.title: Parallelism options
nodes.description: Parallelism options: Various methods and techniques for introducing parallelism in computing systems

nodes.label: GPU
nodes.title: GPU
nodes.description: GPU: Graphics Processing Unit, a specialized electronic circuit designed to accelerate the rendering of images and videos in a computer's display.

nodes.label: GPU introduction
nodes.title: GPU introduction
nodes.description: GPU introduction: An overview of GPU architecture, functionality, and its role in accelerating graphics rendering and parallel computation tasks.

nodes.label: GPU programming model
nodes.title: GPU programming model
nodes.description: GPU programming model: The model used to develop software that leverages the computational power of GPUs

nodes.label: CUDA
nodes.title: CUDA
nodes.description: CUDA: Compute Unified Device Architecture, a parallel computing platform and programming model developed by NVIDIA for GPU-accelerated computing.

nodes.label: Concepts
nodes.title: Concepts
nodes.description: Concepts: concepts include thread, block and Grid

nodes.label: Programming model
nodes.title: Programming model
nodes.description: Programming model: The methodology and constructs used to write GPU-accelerated code, often involving kernel functions, memory management, and synchronization mechanisms.

nodes.label: Optimization
nodes.title: Optimization
nodes.description: Optimization: e.g., using streaming, acynchronious copy, increase occupancy, avoid divergency, smart synchronization, memory coalescing

nodes.label: Performance reasoning
nodes.title: Performance reasoning
nodes.description: Performance reasoning: Methods for analyzing and predicting the performance of GPU-accelerated applications

nodes.label: MPI
nodes.title: MPI
nodes.description: MPI: Message Passing Interface, a standardized and portable message-passing system designed for parallel computing.

nodes.label: MPI introduction
nodes.title: MPI introduction
nodes.description: MPI introduction: Overview of MPI, its purpose, history, and its role in facilitating communication and coordination among distributed processes in parallel computing environments.

nodes.label: MPI programming  model
nodes.title: MPI programming  model
nodes.description: MPI programming  model: The programming paradigm used in MPI applications, involving the creation of distributed processes, communication between processes, and coordination of parallel tasks.

nodes.label: MPI communication
nodes.title: MPI communication
nodes.description: MPI communication: Methods and mechanisms provided by MPI for communication between processes, including point-to-point communication, collective communication, and synchronization primitives.

nodes.label: MPI Data Model
nodes.title: MPI Data Model
nodes.description: MPI Data Model: The conceptual model used by MPI to represent and manipulate data in parallel programs, including concepts such as message buffers, data types, and memory layout.

nodes.label: Derived data type
nodes.title: Derived data type
nodes.description: Derived data type: A user-defined data type in MPI that allows for the creation of complex data structures with non-contiguous memory layouts

nodes.label: Cloud
nodes.title: Cloud
nodes.description: Cloud: A network of remote servers hosted on the internet to store, manage, and process data, providing scalable resources and services on-demand.

nodes.label: Virtualization
nodes.title: Virtualization
nodes.description: Virtualization: Technology that allows multiple virtual instances of operating systems or applications to run on a single physical machine

nodes.label: Service
nodes.title: Service
nodes.description: Service: A component or functionality provided by a system or software, often accessed remotely over a network.

nodes.label: DApp
nodes.title: DApp
nodes.description: DApp: Decentralized Application, a software application that operates on a decentralized network, typically built on blockchain technology and utilizing smart contracts.

nodes.label: Decentralization
nodes.title: Decentralization
nodes.description: Decentralization: Distribution of control and decision-making across multiple nodes or participants in a network, reducing reliance on centralized authorities.

nodes.label: Blockchain
nodes.title: Blockchain
nodes.description: Blockchain: A distributed ledger technology that records transactions across multiple computers in a secure and immutable manner, providing transparency and integrity.

nodes.label: Hash
nodes.title: Hash
nodes.description: Hash: A cryptographic function that converts input data into a fixed-size string of characters, used for data integrity verification and security purposes.

nodes.label: Address
nodes.title: Address
nodes.description: Address: A unique identifier used to designate the location of data or resources in a network or system, such as a blockchain address for digital assets.

nodes.label: Consensus
nodes.title: Consensus
nodes.description: Consensus: The process by which a distributed network agrees on the validity of transactions and maintains a consistent state, often achieved through various consensus mechanisms.

nodes.label: Incentive
nodes.title: Incentive
nodes.description: Incentive: Motivation or reward provided to participants in a system to encourage desired behavior, often used in decentralized networks to incentivize network participation or contribution.

nodes.label: Smart contract
nodes.title: Smart contract
nodes.description: Smart contract: Self-executing contracts with the terms of the agreement directly written into code, automatically enforcing and executing actions when predefined conditions are met, commonly deployed on blockchain platforms.

nodes.label: DApp
nodes.title: DApp
nodes.description: DApp: Decentralized Application, a software application that operates on a decentralized network, typically built on blockchain technology and utilizing smart contracts.
